<div id="Idea_3059"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/3059-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_3059">When Using Novel, More Accessible Techniques, Advertise In Traditional Media&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/4305-4049">Carie Fox and Philip Murphy </a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">7 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">Developing novel techniques meant to involve “more than the usual suspects” needs to be teamed with advertisement in more traditional media.  People can’t come and be excited by a new website unless they know it is there.  For instance, did the website include a Spanish version?  That’s cool, but also not much good unless it was matched with advertisements in Spanish-speakers’ newspapers, or flyers and leaflets in their communities.<br/></div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_3059" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_3059', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2242&topicID=3059')">Comments (0)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_3059"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2242">New Strategies and Techniques</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=foxandmurphy">foxandmurphy</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_3059"></div>
